<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">Anatomy Of The Gluteus Minimus</h2>



<p>The glutes consist of three main muscles: the gluteus maximus, medius, and minimus. The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556144/#:~:text=The%20gluteus%20minimus%20predominantly%20acts,known%20as%20the%20Trendelenburg%20sign." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">gluteus minimus</a> is the smallest of these muscles. It&#8217;s located on the outer side of the hip, just beneath the gluteus medius. </p>



<p>It attaches to the outer surface of the ilium, which is the upper part of the pelvis. It extends to the front of the thigh bone called the femur.</p>



<p>The gluteus minimus helps stabilize the hip and assists in moving the leg away from the body (abduction). It is also involved in keeping the pelvis level when standing on one leg, which is important for balance and walking.</p>


