<h2 class="wp-block-heading faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1623393125914"><strong class="schema-faq-question">What exercise works gluteus minimus?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">The fire hydrant, cable hip abduction, and clamshells specifically target the gluteus minimus. Exercises like glute bridges and Bulgarian split squats also engage the gluteus medius, along with the gluteus maximus and minimus.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1726479390805"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Can you isolate the glute minimus?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">To best isolate the gluteus minimus, use exercises that move your leg away from your body. Some great examples include cable hip abductions, fire hydrants, and clamshells.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1726479391916"><strong class="schema-faq-question">What happens when gluteus minimus is weak?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Weak gluteus minimus can cause balance and <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0966636213006796" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">stability</a> problems during running, walking, and single-leg weight-bearing exercises. It can also cause knee or lower back pain and increase the risks of injuries.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1726479392687"><strong class="schema-faq-question">What causes tight gluteus minimus?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Long sitting, lack of stretching, overuse injuries, and muscle imbalances can all cause tight gluteus minimus. Stretching and strengthening this muscle is key to relieving tightness.</p> </div> </div>
